{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538498"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:28:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:28:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16193"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16193"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.08,0.08,0.05,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8884"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64284"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8884"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16193"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49716"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"2173"},{"type":"tags","id":"2529"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21149"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35709"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43619"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44837"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64284"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with worsening asthma symptoms over three months despite good inhaler technique and compliance. She reports increased wheeze, productive cough with brown mucus plugs, and night sweats. She has had three courses of oral prednisolone in the past year. She has a history of childhood asthma but no other medical conditions. Her medications include fluticasone/salmeterol inhaler and salbutamol as needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. There are scattered wheeze and coarse crackles on chest auscultation. A chest X-ray shows pulmonary infiltrates and central bronchiectasis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sputum microscopy, culture and sensitivity","Aspergillus precipitins","Peripheral blood eosinophil count","Serum galactomannan","Aspergillus-specific IgE"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis (ABPA), including poorly controlled asthma, expectoration of brown mucus plugs, and characteristic radiological findings of fleeting infiltrates and central bronchiectasis. ABPA is an immunological pulmonary disorder caused by hypersensitivity to \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus fumigatus\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspergillus-specific IgE\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the most important diagnostic criteria for ABPA. Elevated levels, along with elevated total IgE (\u0026gt;1000 IU/mL), are central to confirming the diagnosis. The test is both sensitive and specific for ABPA when interpreted in the appropriate clinical context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESputum microscopy, culture and sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E may show \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus\u003C/em\u003E hyphae, but this finding is neither sensitive nor specific for ABPA as the organism can be a coloniser without causing disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspergillus precipitins\u003C/strong\u003E (IgG antibodies) may be positive in ABPA but are also positive in other forms of aspergillosis and are not diagnostic on their own.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeripheral blood eosinophil count\u003C/strong\u003E is often elevated in ABPA but is a non-specific finding that can occur in many other conditions including asthma itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum galactomannan\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used to diagnose invasive aspergillosis and is typically negative in ABPA as there is no tissue invasion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther diagnostic criteria for ABPA include immediate cutaneous reactivity to \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus\u003C/em\u003E antigens, central bronchiectasis, and elevated total IgE. Treatment typically involves systemic corticosteroids and sometimes antifungal agents.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis (ABPA) typically presents in patients with asthma or cystic fibrosis with deteriorating respiratory function.","Elevated total IgE and Aspergillus-specific IgE are key diagnostic criteria for ABPA.","Central bronchiectasis on imaging is a characteristic finding in ABPA."],"references":["Agarwal, Ritesh,; Sehgal, Inderpaul S; Dhooria, Sahajal; Muthu, Valliappan; Prasad, Kuruswamy T.; Bal, Amanjit; Aggarwal, Ashutosh N.; Chakrabarti, Arunaloke. Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis. Indian Journal of Medical Research 151(6):p 529-549, June 2020. | DOI: 10.4103/ijmr.IJMR_1187_19","Greenberger PA, Bush RK, Demain JG, Luong A, Slavin RG, Knutsen AP. Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis. The Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology: In Practice. 2014 Nov 1;2(6):703-8"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49716"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16193"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49716"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T11:13:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T11:14:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8884"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64284"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"att